{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LCYvbMZt1RDVHuYD3meZN1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# How to Set Up Codex\n     2â†’\n     3â†’This guide covers configuring Cloche containers to use\n     4â†’[OpenAI Codex](https://platform.openai.com/docs) as the coding agent.\n     5â†’\n     6â†’## Prerequisites\n     7â†’\n     8â†’- A working Cloche installation ([Installation guide](INSTALL.md))\n     9â†’- An OpenAI API key with Codex access\n    10â†’\n    11â†’## How Authentication Works\n    12â†’\n    13â†’Unlike Claude Code, Codex authenticates via an API key rather than a local session.\n    14â†’You pass your OpenAI API key into containers using environment variables.\n    15â†’\n    16â†’## Dockerfile\n    17â†’\n    18â†’Your `.cloche/Dockerfile` must install the Codex CLI:\n    19â†’\n    20â†’```dockerfile\n    21â†’FROM cloche-base:latest\n    22â†’USER root\n    23â†’\n    24â†’# Install Node.js (required for Codex CLI)\n    25â†’RUN apt-get update \\\n    26â†’    && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends nodejs npm \\\n    27â†’    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n    28â†’\n    29â†’# Install Codex CLI\n    30â†’RUN npm install -g @openai/codex\n    31â†’\n    32â†’# Add your project's build dependencies here\n    33â†’# RUN apt-get install -y ...\n    34â†’\n    35â†’USER agent\n    36â†’```\n    37â†’\n    38â†’## Passing the API Key\n    39â†’\n    40â†’Set `OPENAI_API_KEY` using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` in the daemon's environment:\n    41â†’\n    42â†’```bash\n    43â†’export CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=\"OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\"\n    44â†’cloched &\n    45â†’```\n    46â†’\n    47â†’`CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` accepts comma-separated `KEY=VALUE` pairs and injects them into\n    48â†’every container.\n    49â†’\n    50â†’## Workflow Configuration\n    51â†’\n    52â†’Set `agent_command` to `codex` at the workflow or step level:\n    53â†’\n    54â†’**Workflow level** (applies to all steps):\n    55â†’\n    56â†’```\n    57â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n    58â†’  container {\n    59â†’    agent_command = \"codex\"\n    60â†’  }\n    61â†’\n    62â†’  step implement {\n    63â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    64â†’    results = [success, fail]\n    65â†’  }\n    66â†’\n    67â†’  implement:success -> done\n    68â†’  implement:fail -> abort\n    69â†’}\n    70â†’```\n    71â†’\n    72â†’**Step level** (per-step override):\n    73â†’\n    74â†’```\n    75â†’step implement {\n    76â†’  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    77â†’  agent_command = \"codex\"\n    78â†’  results = [success, fail]\n    79â†’}\n    80â†’```\n    81â†’\n    82â†’Codex is not a \"known\" agent in Cloche, so it receives the prompt on stdin with no\n    83â†’default arguments. Add `agent_args` if the Codex CLI needs specific flags:\n    84â†’\n    85â†’```\n    86â†’step implement {\n    87â†’  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88â†’  agent_command = \"codex\"\n    89â†’  agent_args = \"--full-auto\"\n    90â†’  results = [success, fail]\n    91â†’}\n    92â†’```\n    93â†’\n    94â†’## Fallback Chains\n    95â†’\n    96â†’Use Codex as a fallback if Claude is unavailable:\n    97â†’\n    98â†’```\n    99â†’agent_command = \"claude,codex\"\n   100â†’```\n   101â†’\n   102â†’Or use Codex as the primary with Claude as fallback:\n   103â†’\n   104â†’```\n   105â†’agent_command = \"codex,claude\"\n   106â†’```\n   107â†’\n   108â†’See [Agent Command Resolution](USAGE.md#agent-command-resolution) for full fallback\n   109â†’semantics.\n   110â†’\n   111â†’## Verifying the Setup\n   112â†’\n   113â†’Run a quick test workflow:\n   114â†’\n   115â†’```bash\n   116â†’cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Print hello world\"\n   117â†’```\n   118â†’\n   119â†’Check logs to confirm Codex is executing:\n   120â†’\n   121â†’```bash\n   122â†’cloche logs <run-id>\n   123â†’```\n   124â†’\n   125â†’## Troubleshooting\n   126â†’\n   127â†’**Codex not found in container**: Make sure your Dockerfile installs `@openai/codex`\n   128â†’via npm and that Node.js is available.\n   129â†’\n   130â†’**Authentication errors**: Verify that `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` includes a valid\n   131â†’`OPENAI_API_KEY`. You can check by inspecting the container's environment:\n   132â†’\n   133â†’```bash\n   134â†’docker exec <container-id> env | grep OPENAI\n   135â†’```\n   136â†’\n   137â†’**No output from Codex**: Since Codex is not a known agent, Cloche passes the prompt\n   138â†’on stdin. Ensure the Codex CLI version you installed supports reading prompts from\n   139â†’stdin, or set appropriate `agent_args`.\n   140â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ea6a4db-317b-4116-946b-dfa5f420f957","uuid":"754ed318-fb08-4602-87d1-90171c78471c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/agent-setup-codex.md","content":"# How to Set Up Codex\n\nThis guide covers configuring Cloche containers to use\n[OpenAI Codex](https://platform.openai.com/docs) as the coding agent.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n- A working Cloche installation ([Installation guide](INSTALL.md))\n- An OpenAI API key with Codex access\n\n## How Authentication Works\n\nUnlike Claude Code, Codex authenticates via an API key rather than a local session.\nYou pass your OpenAI API key into containers using environment variables.\n\n## Dockerfile\n\nYour `.cloche/Dockerfile` must install the Codex CLI:\n\n```dockerfile\nFROM cloche-base:latest\nUSER root\n\n# Install Node.js (required for Codex CLI)\nRUN apt-get update \\\n    && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends nodejs npm \\\n    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n# Install Codex CLI\nRUN npm install -g @openai/codex\n\n# Add your project's build dependencies here\n# RUN apt-get install -y ...\n\nUSER agent\n```\n\n## Passing the API Key\n\nSet `OPENAI_API_KEY` using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` in the daemon's environment:\n\n```bash\nexport CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=\"OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\"\ncloched &\n```\n\n`CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` accepts comma-separated `KEY=VALUE` pairs and injects them into\nevery container.\n\n## Workflow Configuration\n\nSet `agent_command` to `codex` at the workflow or step level:\n\n**Workflow level** (applies to all steps):\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"codex\"\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> done\n  implement:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n**Step level** (per-step override):\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  agent_command = \"codex\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\nCodex is not a \"known\" agent in Cloche, so it receives the prompt on stdin with no\ndefault arguments. Add `agent_args` if the Codex CLI needs specific flags:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  agent_command = \"codex\"\n  agent_args = \"--full-auto\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n## Fallback Chains\n\nUse Codex as a fallback if Claude is unavailable:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"claude,codex\"\n```\n\nOr use Codex as the primary with Claude as fallback:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"codex,claude\"\n```\n\nSee [Agent Command Resolution](USAGE.md#agent-command-resolution) for full fallback\nsemantics.\n\n## Verifying the Setup\n\nRun a quick test workflow:\n\n```bash\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Print hello world\"\n```\n\nCheck logs to confirm Codex is executing:\n\n```bash\ncloche logs <run-id>\n```\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n**Codex not found in container**: Make sure your Dockerfile installs `@openai/codex`\nvia npm and that Node.js is available.\n\n**Authentication errors**: Verify that `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` includes a valid\n`OPENAI_API_KEY`. You can check by inspecting the container's environment:\n\n```bash\ndocker exec <container-id> env | grep OPENAI\n```\n\n**No output from Codex**: Since Codex is not a known agent, Cloche passes the prompt\non stdin. Ensure the Codex CLI version you installed supports reading prompts from\nstdin, or set appropriate `agent_args`.\n","numLines":140,"startLine":1,"totalLines":140}}}
